The Keepers of Measure were the earliest civilization to leave functional records.
They governed through calibration: road stones aligned to stars, graded cisterns, caravan levies in water rights.
Their writing system, Measure Script, encoded direction, volume, legal status, and time in single glyphs.
Mismeasurement was a civic offense.

They built the eastern road network as a legal-hydraulic system.
Twelve Obelisk Lines marked travel windows, ration days, and convoy departures.
Charter stones recorded distance, toll rates, and witness seals at regular intervals.

At the Great Oasis they built the Cistern Ring (first hydraulic regulation), the Measuring House (observatory-archive-courthouse), and the Waystone Circle (geometric reference for all desert roads).

Their axiom: "What is unrecorded becomes famine." This was literal.
The Black Sun Shard's memory-erosion forced all records into stone because verbal agreements were forgotten.
The Solar Court later conscripted their road-taxation apparatus for theological use.
Kowloon's Jade Clerks preserved the closest descendant of Measure Script.
Their roads, cisterns, and obelisk foundations still shape eastern desert geography.
